<subSubSection id="C3546563993D115CFD76FB07FCDAFB26" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF136E8993D115CFD76FB07FCDAFB26" blockId="60.[700,1229,193,1419]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
ETYMOLOGY: From the Latin 
<emphasis id="B93AEAFA993D115CFB99FB07FBC9FB7E" box="[1078,1146,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">cornu</emphasis>
(horn) and the Latin suffix ­ 
<emphasis id="B93AEAFA993D115CFC14FB29FC58FB60" box="[955,1003,1191,1214]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">atus</emphasis>
(having the nature of). I refer to the horn like configuration of the parameres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3546563993D115CFD76FB70FD5EFA55" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF136E8993D115CFD76FB70FD5EFA55" blockId="60.[700,1229,193,1419]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
